\section{Selection}
Evidence of natural selection is often used as a measure of the functionality of a region, or of it's usefulness to an organism. For example, there is a database of the conservation of each nucleotide in the human genome that is used to calculate the likelihood that the specific nucleotide is useful. The idea is that the more conserved a nucleotide, or region is, the more likely it is to do something useful, or to lead to disease when disrupted. Evidence of selection has therefore been used to determine the likelihood that RTs are effecting genes in some functional way. 

